05748nam a22009855i 9780271088495DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710884957 a10.1515/97802710884952doi  a(DE-B1597)584406  a(OCoLC)1253313897  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPQ4053.E26bC47 2020eb 7aLIT0042002bisacsh04a850.9/35532231 aCesaretti, Enrico, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aElemental Narratives :bReading Environmental Entanglements in Modern Italy /cEnrico Cesaretti. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnthropoScene: The SLSA Book Series ;v600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Elemental Narratives -- t1. Modernist Matters -- t2. Slick Territories: Petroculture, Italian Style -- t3. Apua Ma(t)ter: Narratives of Marble -- t4. Steel and Asbestos: Stories of Toxic Lands and Bodies in Tuscany and Beyond -- t5. Concrete and Asphalt: Geographies of Environmental Disruption in Modern Italy -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past century, the Italian landscape has undergone exceedingly rapid transformations, shifting from a mostly rural environment to a decidedly modern world. This changing landscape is endowed with a narrative agency that transforms how we understand our surroundings. Situated at the juncture of Italian studies and ecocriticism and following the recent “material turn” in the environmental humanities, Elemental Narratives outlines an original cultural and environmental map of the bel paese. Giving equal weight to readings of fiction, nonfiction, works of visual art, and physical sites, Enrico Cesaretti investigates the interconnected stories emerging from both human creativity and the expressive eloquence of “glocal” materials, such as sulfur, petroleum, marble, steel, and asbestos, that have helped make and, simultaneously, “un-make” today’s Italy, affecting its socio-environmental health in multiple ways. Embracing the idea of a decentralized agency that is shared among human and nonhuman entities, Cesaretti suggests that engaging with these entangled discursive and material texts is a sound and revealing ecocritical practice that promises to generate new knowledge and more participatory, affective responses to environmental issues, both in Italy and elsewhere. Ultimately, he argues that complementing quantitative, data-based information with insights from fiction and nonfiction, the arts, and other humanistic disciplines is both desirable and crucial if we want to modify perceptions and attitudes, increase our awareness and understanding, and, in turn, develop more sustainable worldviews in the era of the Anthropocene. Elegantly written and convincingly argued, this book will appeal broadly to scholars and students working in the fields of environmental studies, comparative literatures, ecocriticism, environmental history, and Italian studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aEcology in literature. 0aEnvironmentalism in literature. 0aItalian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aItalian literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPollution in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh  aEcocriticism.  aEcology in literature.  aItalian environment.  aItalian literature.  aItalian petroculture.  aItalian toxic autobiographies.  aItaly.  aLandscapes in literature.  aNature in literature.  aasbestos.  acement.  aecomaterialism.  aentanglement.  aenvironmental humanities and Italy. 